{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### **Cl. 2 Investigation: Infinite Surds**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Infinite Surds**\n",
    "\n",
    "To begin, the question asks us to consider the following as an example of an infinite surd:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\sqrt{1+\\sqrt{1+\\sqrt{1+\\sqrt{1+...}}}}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Where $n$ is the number of square roots there are inside of the expression and $a_n$ is the result of the produced expression for example:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "a_1 = \\sqrt{1+\\sqrt{1}} \\\\\\\n",
    "a_2 = \\sqrt{1+\\sqrt{1 + \\sqrt{1}}} \\\\\\\n",
    "a_2 = \\sqrt{1+\\sqrt{1 + \\sqrt{1 + \\sqrt{1}}}} \\\\\\\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "To begin, we first found an equation for term $a_{n+1}$ in terms of $a_n$: $a_{n+1} = \\sqrt{1 + a_n}$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Part 1: Investigation for $\\sqrt{1+\\sqrt{1 + ...}}$**\n",
    "\n",
    "In this section, we will analyse the values and relationships between $a_n$, and $n$ with Python for easier comprehension but in order to do this, we must first setup the neccessary environment and get the required dependencies to graph our data and analyse the results."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 25,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Requirement already satisfied: matplotlib in /Users/alan/Documents/Coding/infinite_surds/env/lib/python3.11/site-packages (3.9.2)\n",
      "Requirement already satisfied: contourpy>=1.0.1 in /Users/alan/Documents/Coding/infinite_surds/env/lib/python3.11/site-packages (from matplotlib) (1.3.0)\n",
      "Requirement already satisfied: cycler>=0.10 in /Users/alan/Documents/Coding/infinite_surds/env/lib/python3.11/site-packages (from matplotlib) (0.12.1)\n",
      "Requirement already satisfied: fonttools>=4.22.0 in /Users/alan/Documents/Coding/infinite_surds/env/lib/python3.11/site-packages (from matplotlib) (4.54.1)\n",
      "Requirement already satisfied: kiwisolver>=1.3.1 in /Users/alan/Documents/Coding/infinite_surds/env/lib/python3.11/site-packages (from matplotlib) (1.4.7)\n",
      "Requirement already satisfied: numpy>=1.23 in /Users/alan/Documents/Coding/infinite_surds/env/lib/python3.11/site-packages (from matplotlib) (2.1.1)\n",
      "Requirement already satisfied: packaging>=20.0 in /Users/alan/Documents/Coding/infinite_surds/env/lib/python3.11/site-packages (from matplotlib) (24.1)\n",
      "Requirement already satisfied: pillow>=8 in /Users/alan/Documents/Coding/infinite_surds/env/lib/python3.11/site-packages (from matplotlib) (10.4.0)\n",
      "Requirement already satisfied: pyparsing>=2.3.1 in /Users/alan/Documents/Coding/infinite_surds/env/lib/python3.11/site-packages (from matplotlib) (3.1.4)\n",
      "Requirement already satisfied: python-dateutil>=2.7 in /Users/alan/Documents/Coding/infinite_surds/env/lib/python3.11/site-packages (from matplotlib) (2.9.0.post0)\n",
      "Requirement already satisfied: six>=1.5 in /Users/alan/Documents/Coding/infinite_surds/env/lib/python3.11/site-packages (from python-dateutil>=2.7->matplotlib) (1.16.0)\n",
      "\n",
      "\u001b[1m[\u001b[0m\u001b[34;49mnotice\u001b[0m\u001b[1;39;49m]\u001b[0m\u001b[39;49m A new release of pip is available: \u001b[0m\u001b[31;49m23.2.1\u001b[0m\u001b[39;49m -> \u001b[0m\u001b[32;49m24.2\u001b[0m\n",
      "\u001b[1m[\u001b[0m\u001b[34;49mnotice\u001b[0m\u001b[1;39;49m]\u001b[0m\u001b[39;49m To update, run: \u001b[0m\u001b[32;49mpip install --upgrade pip\u001b[0m\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Import all neccesary dependencies to graph the relationships in the next section\n",
    "import sys\n",
    "!{sys.executable} -m pip install matplotlib"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Get all neccesary imports\n",
    "import math\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from typing import TypedDict"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class GenResult(TypedDict):\n",
    "    table: list[tuple[int, float]]\n",
    "    a: float\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define the function to generate the sequence\n",
    "# num: int - The number to generate the sequence for e.g. num=1 will generate the sequence for sqrt(1 + sqrt(1 + sqrt(1 + ...)))\n",
    "def generate(num: int = 1, n: int = 1, prev: float = 1.0, table_ref: list = None) -> GenResult:\n",
    "    if table_ref is None:\n",
    "        table_ref = []\n",
    "    \n",
    "    a_n = math.sqrt(num + prev)\n",
    "    table_ref.append((n, round(a_n, 6)))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    if abs(a_n - prev) < 0.00001:\n",
    "        return GenResult(table=table_ref, a=round(a_n, 6))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return generate(num, n + 1, a_n, table_ref)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next following the document provided and the code written above, we will use a simple python function `generate` to generate the a `table` between the values of `a_n` and `n` and we plot it on a cartesian plane to see the general trend of the relationship between `a_n` and `n`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 55,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "result_1 = generate(1)\n",
    "\n",
    "x_values = [x[0] for x in result_1['table']]\n",
    "y_values = [y[1] for y in result_1['table']]\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.rcParams['text.usetex'] = False\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.plot(x_values, y_values)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('$n$')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('$a_n$')\n",
    "plt.title('$a_n$ vs $n$')\n",
    "\n",
    "column_labels = ['$n$', '$a_n$']\n",
    "\n",
    "table_data = [[x, y] for x, y in zip(x_values, y_values)]\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.table(cellText=table_data, colLabels=column_labels, loc='right', cellLoc='left')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In the graph generated, one may notice that there is a *positive correlation* between $a_n$ and $n$ where as $n$ increases, so does $a_n$ although the graph does begin to level out quite quickly after $n=4$ before appearing to almost completely level out after $n=6$. This suggests that the difference of  $|a_n - a_{n+1}|$ will get less and less, and approach zero as $n$ gets larger and larger. This is since the magnitude of increase between $a_n$ and $a_{n+1}$ is gets less and less with every increase of n. This can also be shown with the following graph shown below."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 56,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x_diff = [i for i in range(len(result_1['table']) - 1)]\n",
    "y_diff = []\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(len(result_1['table']) - 1):\n",
    "    diff = abs(round(result_1['table'][i][1] - result_1['table'][i + 1][1], 6))\n",
    "    y_diff.append(diff)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.rcParams['text.usetex'] = False\n",
    "plt.plot(x_diff, y_diff)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('$n$')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('$|a_n - a_{n+1}|$')\n",
    "plt.title('$n$ vs. $|a_n - a_{n+1}|$')\n",
    "\n",
    "table_data_diff = [[x, y] for x, y in zip(x_diff, y_diff)]\n",
    "column_labels_diff = ['n', '$|a_n - a_{n+1}|$']\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.table(cellText=table_data_diff, colLabels=column_labels_diff, loc='right', cellLoc='left')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As exemplified by the graphed trend, we may notice that the difference of $|a_n - a_n+1|$ approaches zero as the value $n$ approaches infinity. With this knowledge we can find the final value of $\\sqrt{1+\\sqrt{1 + ...}}$ by reason that when $n=\\infty$, $a_n - a_{n+1}$ is equal to $0$. Thus we can infer that when $n$ is $\\infty$, $a_n = a_{n+1}$. With this knowledge, we can set up the following algebraic system of equations.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "a_{n+1} = \\sqrt{1 + a_n}\\\\\n",
    "\n",
    "\\because a_{n+1} = a_n\\\\\n",
    "\\therefore a_n = \\sqrt{1 + a_n}\\\\\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Now, we solve for a quadratic equation where $ax^2 + bx + c = 0$\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "a_n^2 = 1 + a_n\\\\\n",
    "a_n^2 - a_n - 1 = 0\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "We plug this into the quadratic formula where $a_n = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}$:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "a_n = \\frac{-(-1) \\pm \\sqrt{(-1)^2 - 4(1)(-1)}}{2(1)}\\\\\n",
    "a_n = \\frac{-(-1) \\pm \\sqrt{5}}{2}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Thus we can propose that $a_n = \\frac{-(-1) \\pm \\sqrt{5}}{2}$ due to the solving and reasons above."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Part 2: Investigation for $\\sqrt{2+\\sqrt{2 + ...}}$**\n",
    "\n",
    "For the second part of this investigation, we are to consider a similar situation but where instead of the surd being $\\sqrt{1+\\sqrt{1 + ...}}$ it will be $\\sqrt{2+\\sqrt{2 + ...}}$. Like the question from earlier, we can come up with the formula that $a_{n+1} = \\sqrt{2 + a_n}$.\n",
    "To begin, we will repeat the process from above, and find the relationship between $a_n$ and $n$:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 57,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "result_2 = generate(2)\n",
    "\n",
    "x_values2 = [x[0] for x in result_2['table']]\n",
    "y_values2 = [y[1] for y in result_2['table']]\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.rcParams['text.usetex'] = False\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.plot(x_values, y_values)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('$n$')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('$a_n$')\n",
    "plt.title('$a_n$ vs. $n$')\n",
    "table_data2 = [[x, y] for x, y in zip(x_values2, y_values2)]\n",
    "\n",
    "table = plt.table(cellText=table_data2, colLabels=column_labels, loc='right', cellLoc='left')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "From this graph, we can observe that $a_n$ once again levels out as $n$ increases.\n",
    "\n",
    "With this knowledge, we can reason once again that $|a_n - a_{n+1}|$ will approach zero as $n$ approaches $\\infty\\$. But to make sure our assumption is right, we will graph it out once again like before and observe the trend between $n$ and $|a_n - a_{n+1}|$:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 58,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x_diff2 = [i for i in range(len(result_2['table']) - 1)]\n",
    "y_diff2 = []\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(len(result_2['table']) - 1):\n",
    "    diff = abs(round(result_2['table'][i][1] - result_2['table'][i + 1][1], 6))\n",
    "    y_diff2.append(diff)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.rcParams['text.usetex'] = False\n",
    "plt.plot(x_diff2, y_diff2)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('$n$')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('$|a_n - a_{n+1}|$')\n",
    "plt.title('$n$ vs. $|a_n - a_{n+1}|$')\n",
    "\n",
    "table_data_diff2 = [[x, y] for x, y in zip(x_diff2, y_diff2)]\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.table(cellText=table_data_diff2, colLabels=column_labels_diff, loc='right', cellLoc='left')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As predicted, the plotted graph of $n$ vs. $|a_n - a_{n+1}|$ shows that as $n$ reaches its limit, $|a_n - a_{n+1}|$ approaches zero, thus we can use the same method to find a solution to this expression as we had earlier.\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "a_n = \\sqrt{2 + a_n}\\\\\n",
    "a_n^2 - a_n - 2 = 0\\\\\n",
    "a_n = \\frac{-(-1) \\pm \\sqrt{(-1)^2-4(1)(-2)}}{2}\\\\\n",
    "a_n = \\frac{1 \\pm \\sqrt{9}}{2}\\\\\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Thus, we can come to the conclusion that $a_n = \\frac{1 \\pm \\sqrt{9}}{2}$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Part 3: Investigation for $\\sqrt{k+\\sqrt{k + ...}}$**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, we will attempt to find a general formula for $\\sqrt{k+\\sqrt{k + ...}}$ where k is a positive number integer and where the first term is $\\sqrt{k+\\sqrt{k}}$. Like before, we will use the same to solve for $a_n$ in this situation by reasoning that when $n$ reaches it's limit, $a_n = a_{n+1}$. Firstly, according the previous formula to solve for $a_{n+1}$ with $a_n$ we can infer that $a_{n+1} = \\sqrt{k + a_n}$. Then, we can do the following\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "a_n = \\sqrt{k + a_n}\\\\\n",
    "a_n^2 = k + a_n\\\\\n",
    "a_n^2 - a_n - k = 0\\\\\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Plugging this into the quadratic formula we will get the following:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "a_n = \\frac{-(-1) \\pm \\sqrt{(-1)^2 - 4(1)(-k)}}{2(1)}\\\\\n",
    "a_n = \\frac{1 \\pm \\sqrt{1 + 4k}}{2}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Thus, we can conclude that $\\sqrt{k+\\sqrt{k + ...}}$ would be equal to $\\frac{1 \\pm \\sqrt{1 + 4k}}{2}$, which would be the general statement for infinite surds."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Conclusion and final remarks**\n",
    "\n",
    "In this investigation, we have discovered the general statement representing all infinite using patterns that we found when $k=1$ and $k=2$. The scope of this statement seems to include $k$ being an irrational and rational number as long as $k > 0$."
   ]
  }
 ],
